      <section environment="" chapter_type="" type="Section" wbtag="section" title="Limits of Functions on the Real Line" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" num="1" serial="3.1">
        <title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="title" scope="section" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="3.1" slide="">
          <newline course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="title"/>
          <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="title" wbtag="paragraphs">Limits of Functions on the Real Line</paragraphs>
          <newline course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="title"/>
        </title>
        <slides environment="" chapter_type="">
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" canon_num="3" scope="section" id="s3" slide="3" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Limits of Functions on the Real Line">
            <keywords slide="3" environ="slide" chapter="3" course="Math 1010">
              <keyword chapter="3" slide="3">limit</keyword>
            </keywords>
            <title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="title" scope="section" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="3">
              <newline course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="title"/>
              <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="title" wbtag="paragraphs">Limits of Functions on the Real Line</paragraphs>
              <newline course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="title"/>
            </title>
            <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> Let $f : A \longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$ be a function, where $A \subseteq \mathbb{R}$.
Let $a$ be a point on the real line such that $f$ is defined on a neighborhood of $a$
(though not necessarily at $a$ itself). </paragraphs>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="1" md5="5c994a41945c604af63752bba494ca7a" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" slide="3" item="3.1">
              <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> We say that the </paragraphs>
              <inline_keyword course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement">limit</inline_keyword>
              <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> of $f$ at $a$ is $L$ if for all $\varepsilon &gt; 0$,
there exists $\delta &gt; 0$ such that $\abs{f(x) - L} &lt; \varepsilon$
whenever $x$ satisfies $0 &lt; \abs{x - a} &lt; \delta$. </paragraphs>
            </statement>
            <newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
              <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> If $f$ has a limit $L$ at $a$, we write:
\[
\lim_{x \rightarrow a} f(x) = L.
\]
Note that the limit may exist even if
$a$ does not lie in the domain of $f$. </paragraphs>
            </newcol>
            <newline course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
            <substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Remark" wbtag="remark" md5="4406c29c190be7ebd7d2eabd26b46296" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" slide="3">
              <newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
                <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Intuitively, $\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow a} f(x) = L$ means that the 
value $f(x)$ approaches $L$ as $x$ approaches $a$ from either side, or that $f(x)$
is very near $L$ whenever $x$ is very near $a$. Obviously, the term "near"
is somewhat vague, and it is precisely because of this vagueness that mathematicians
feel the need to define limits rigorously using the "$\delta$-$\varepsilon$" language. </paragraphs>
              </newcol>
            </substatement>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="2" md5="0a26d350fc271e6ccb404fe0d8289f2e" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" slide="3" item="3.2">
              <newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
                <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Consider $f(x) = \dfrac{x^2 - 4}{x + 2}$.
Note that the function $f$ is not defined at $-2$.</paragraphs>
                <newline course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol"/>
                <collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Observe that for $x$ near $-2$, for example, $x = -2.001$, or $x = -1.9999$, 
we have:
\[
f(-2.001) = -4.001,
\]
\[
f(-1.9999) = -3.9999,
\]
which are close to $-4$.</paragraphs>
                  <newline course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol"/>
                  <collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
                    <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Moreover, as $x$ "approaches" $-2$ ($x = -2.001, -2.0001, -2.00001, \ldots$),
we have $f(x) = -4.001, -4.0001, -4.00001$. So, it appears $f(x)$ approaches $-4$
as $x$ approaches $-2$. This suggests that the limit of $f(x)$ at $x = -2$ is:
\[
\lim_{x \rightarrow -2} f(x) = -4.
\] </paragraphs>
                    <collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
                      <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> This turns out to be true, and is not surprising, since we can rewrite $f(x)$ as follows: </paragraphs>
                      <steps course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="steps" stepsid="steps1">
\[
\begin{split}
f(x) &amp;= \begin{cases}
\dfrac{(x + 2)(x - 2)}{x + 2},&amp; \text{if}\; x \neq -2;\\
\text{undefined},&amp; \text{if}\; x = -2.
\end{cases}
\\&amp;
\class{steps}{\cssId{step0}{= \begin{cases}
x - 2,&amp; \text{if}\; x \neq -2;\\
\text{undefined},&amp; \text{if}\; x = -2.
\end{cases}}}
\end{split}
\]
</steps>
                      <collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
                        <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Hence, all along we have really been asking what $x - 2$ tends to as $x$ tends to $-2$. </paragraphs>
                      </collapse>
                    </collapse>
                  </collapse>
                </collapse>
              </newcol>
            </statement>
          </slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" canon_num="4" id="s4" slide="4" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Limits of Functions on the Real Line">
            <keywords slide="4" environ="slide" chapter="3" course="Math 1010">
              <keyword chapter="3" slide="4">limit</keyword>
            </keywords>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="3" md5="6c810d9579acf5113da2eaab3f50dfb6" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" slide="4" item="3.3">
              <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> Let $f : A \longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$ be a function, where $A \subseteq \mathbb{R}$
is unbounded towards $+\infty$ and/or $-\infty$.
We say that the </paragraphs>
              <inline_keyword course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement">limit</inline_keyword>
              <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> of $f$ at $\infty$ (resp. $-\infty$)
is $L$ if for all $\varepsilon &gt; 0$,
there exists a $c \in \mathbb{R}$  such that $\abs{f(x) - L} &lt; \varepsilon$
whenever $x &gt; c$ (resp. $x &lt; c$). </paragraphs>
            </statement>
            <newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
              <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> If $f$ has a limit $L$ at $\infty$ (resp $-\infty$), we write:
\[
\lim_{x \rightarrow \infty} f(x) = L
\quad
\left( \text{resp. }
\lim_{x \rightarrow -\infty} f(x) = L
\right)
\] </paragraphs>
            </newcol>
          </slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" canon_num="5" id="s5" slide="5" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Limits of Functions on the Real Line">
            <keywords slide="5" environ="slide" chapter="3" course="Math 1010"/>
            <strong xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
              <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Some Useful Identities:</paragraphs>
            </strong>
            <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""/>
            <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs"> In the following idenities,
the symbol $a$ can be either a real number or $\pm \infty$. </paragraphs>
            <col_ol course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_ol">
              <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> For any constant $c \in \mathbb{R}$,
we have $\displaystyle\lim_{x\rightarrow a} c = c$. </paragraphs>
              </col_li>
              <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\displaystyle\lim_{x \rightarrow a} x = a.$ </paragraphs>
              </col_li>
              <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> If $\lim_{x \rightarrow a} f(x) = L$, and $\lim_{x \rightarrow a} g(x) = M$,
then: </paragraphs>
                <col_ul course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_ul">
                  <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_li">
                    <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\lim_{x\rightarrow a} (f\pm g)(x) = L\pm M.$ </paragraphs>
                  </col_li>
                  <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_li">
                    <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\lim_{x\rightarrow a} fg(x) = LM.$ </paragraphs>
                  </col_li>
                  <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_li">
                    <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="paragraphs"> \[\lim_{x\rightarrow a} \dfrac{f}{g}(x) = \dfrac{L}{M}\] provided that $M \neq 0$. </paragraphs>
                  </col_li>
                </col_ul>
              </col_li>
              <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> If $\lim_{x \rightarrow a} f(x) = L$, then:
\[
\lim_{x\rightarrow a}(f(x))^n = L^n\quad
\text{ for all } n \in \mathbb{N} = \{1, 2, 3, \ldots\},
\]
and
\[
\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\sqrt[n]{f(x)} = \sqrt[n]{L}\quad
\text{ for all odd positive integers } n.
\] </paragraphs>
                <newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> In particular, for all positive integer $n$, we have:
\[
\lim_{x \rightarrow } x^n = a^n.
\] </paragraphs>
                </newcol>
              </col_li>
              <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> If $\lim_{x \rightarrow a} f(x) = L &gt; 0$, then $\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\sqrt[n]{f(x)} = \sqrt[n]{L}$ for all $n \in \mathbb{N}$. </paragraphs>
              </col_li>
            </col_ol>
          </slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" canon_num="6" id="s6" slide="6" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Limits of Functions on the Real Line">
            <keywords slide="6" environ="slide" chapter="3" course="Math 1010"/>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="4" md5="19d013c26c7ccb4ea192354f43700a01" course="Math 1010" chapter="3" slide="6" item="3.4">
              <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> Compute the following limits, if they exist: </paragraphs>
              <col_ul course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_ul">
                <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\displaystyle  \lim_{x \to -1} \frac{x^2-1}{x^2 - 5x - 6}$ </paragraphs>
                <hr xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ul"/>
                <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_li"/>
                <col_li course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="col_li">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 1010" chapter="3" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ul" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 4} \frac{2-\sqrt{x}}{16-x^2}$ </paragraphs>
                </col_li>
              </col_ul>
            </statement>
          </slide>
        </slides>
      </section>
